liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: No, it's not just another Elvis biopic. Priscilla, directed by Sofia Coppola and based on Priscilla Presley 's 1985 autobiography, Elvis and Me, has just premiered at the Venice Film Festival. The film, depicting Priscilla's roller-coaster life with one of the most famous figures of the 20th century, stars Cailee Spaeny in the title role and Australian actor Jacob Elordi as Elvis. At the premiere, Priscilla said the legendary rock star had been the love of her life, despite eventually leaving him. "It wasn't that I didn't love him. He was the love of my life, but it was the lifestyle that was so difficult for me," Priscilla told reporters. Priscilla met Elvis in 1959 when she was just 14 and he was deeply homesick, stationed with the US army in West Germany. The film is set to be released in the US on October 27, and hopefully, Australia isn't too far behind.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Priscilla, directed by Sofia Coppola, premieres at Venice

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The wait is over! The Rolling Stones have announced their first album in 18 years — since 2005's A Bigger Bang. Titled Hackney Diamonds, the band will share details of the release at an event in East London's Hackney district on Wednesday, where they'll be interviewed live by The Tonight Show host Jimmy Fallon. "Hackney may be at the heart of Hackney Diamonds, but this is a truly global moment we want to share with fans around the world via YouTube," the Rolling Stones shared in a statement. The album is also the Stones' first since the death of drummer Charlie Watts in 2021.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A group of federal politicians will head to the United States this month to lobby for the release of Julian Assange. The US is seeking to extradite the WikiLeaks founder from London, on charges of espionage. Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has previously expressed frustration that a diplomatic solution for Julian Assange's case has not been reached. The delegation that will head to the US includes Nationals MP Barnaby Joyce, Labor MP Tony Zappia and Independent MP Monique Ryan. It comes ahead of Albanese's trip to Washington in October.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Westpac has apologised for not responding to hardship applications. As reported below, the corporate regulator is suing ASIC for allegedly failing to respond to 229 applications for hardship assistance in the required 21 days, between 2015 and 2022. The bank says over this period it received about 630,000 applications for hardship assistance. Westpac Group Chief Information Officer Scott Collary says it has strengthened and upgraded its processes. "This error meant we didn't provide some of our customers with the help they needed. For this, we are deeply sorry. While we have assisted some of these customers in subsequent contact, it is not good enough that we missed their initial attempt to get in touch." The bank says since uncovering the issue it has contacted the affected customers and completed a remediation program including refunds of fees and interest, debt waivers and payments for non-financial loss, totalling about $900,000. Westpac says it self-reported the incident to ASIC and is cooperating with their investigation.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Westpac responds to allegations

children.content: Westpac has apologised for not responding to hardship applications.
As reported below, the corporate regulator is suing ASIC for allegedly failing to respond to 229 applications for hardship assistance in the required 21 days, between 2015 and 2022.
The bank says over this period it received about 630,000 applications for hardship assistance.
Westpac Group Chief Information Officer Scott Collary says it has strengthened and upgraded its processes.
"This error meant we didn't provide some of our customers with the help they needed. For this, we are deeply sorry.
While we have assisted some of these customers in subsequent contact, it is not good enough that we missed their initial attempt to get in touch."

The bank says since uncovering the issue it has contacted the affected customers and completed a remediation program including refunds of fees and interest, debt waivers and payments for non-financial loss, totalling about $900,000.
Westpac says it self-reported the incident to ASIC and is cooperating with their investigation.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian Securities and Investments Commission (ASIC) has launched legal action against Westpac Bank for failing to respond to customers' hardship notices. ASIC alleges that 229 customers did not receive a response to their hardship notice within the required time frame of 21 days. Submitting a hardship notice results in a change to the credit contract. This was an ongoing issue with the online hardship notice process between 2015 and 2022. ASIC Deputy Chair Sarah Court says submitting a hardship notice can be a lifeline for people experiencing challenging financial circumstances. "ASIC has taken this action to highlight the importance of lenders responding to hardship notices within the required time frame to reduce harm to their customers. Westpac's failures to respond to these notices compounded their customers' difficult financial circumstances." The regulator claims Westpac did not do enough to investigate and rectify the systems issues it was experiencing. It is seeking declarations, pecuniary penalties and adverse publicity orders against Westpac from the court. A date for the first hearing is yet to be scheduled.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Corporate regulator sues Westpac
